      "question": "Two pillars of equal height $h$ stand on opposite sides of a road which is $80$ $m$ wide. At a point between the pillars on the road, the angles of elevation of the tops of the pillars are $60^\\circ$ and $30^\\circ$ respectively. Find the height of the pillars and the position of the point from the first pillar.",
      "answer": "$h = 20\\sqrt{3}$ $m$, distance = $20$ $m$",
      "solution": {
        "steps": [
          "Let the height of both pillars be $h$. Let the total width of the road be $BC = 80$ $m$. Let $P$ be a point on the road such that $BP = x$ and $PC = 80 - x$.",
          "In $\\triangle ABP$, $\\tan 60^\\circ = \\frac{h}{x}$, which gives $h = x\\sqrt{3}$.",
          "In $\\triangle DCP$, $\\tan 30^\\circ = \\frac{h}{80-x}$, which gives $h = \\frac{80-x}{\\sqrt{3}}$.",
          "Equate the two expressions for $h$: $x\\sqrt{3} = \\frac{80-x}{\\sqrt{3}}$. Solving for $x$ gives $3x = 80 - x$, so $4x = 80$, $x = 20$ $m$.",
          "Substitute $x = 20$ into $h = x\\sqrt{3}$ to get $h = 20\\sqrt{3}$ $m$."
        ],
        "derivation": "$h = x\\tan 60^\\circ = x\\sqrt{3} \\\\ h = (80-x)\\tan 30^\\circ = \\frac{80-x}{\\sqrt{3}} \\\\ x\\sqrt{3} = \\frac{80-x}{\\sqrt{3}} \\\\ 3x = 80 - x \\\\ 4x = 80 \\Rightarrow x = 20 \\\\ h = 20\\sqrt{3} \\approx 34.64$ $m$"
      },
